^^^^^^^^^^Tic tac toe is among the simplest of competitive games, but that does not imply that its mastery is easy for a person.  Our subject needed more than two years to progress from novice to mature play.  Setting the interpretation in a framework which relates the child's social context to the personal construction of mind, we model her relevant cognitive structures throughout the development and observe how stage-like characteristics of behavior can be seen as emerging from incremental structural changes.  Specifically, we observe how the serial alteration of opponents' roles which is necessary to game length mental play derives from the progressive elaboration of cognitive structures whose initial functions are largely pattern-driven and insensitive to an opponent's moves.

The Corpus^^^^^^^^One aspect of the corpus may be surprising: the observations are complete.  The materials are a thematic extract from THE INTIMATE STUDY,   a six months long naturalistic study of one child's mental development.  The completeness was possible because the child, Miriam, is my daughter.  For the six months of The Intimate Study, we were constant companions, and Miriam was under constant observation.  The situations of our play were typically informal, but the observation was not.  Most of the material to be presented here is from transcriptions of mechanically recorded sessions.  Naturalistic observation filled the gaps of recording.  Observations from the following two years are cited  to trace Miriam's appreciation of opening advantage, her invention of a new strategic objective, and a "final" level of performance. All her publicly manifest behavior relevant to Tic tac toe is captured in the corpus of twenty three Tic^tac^toe sessions and a significant selection of that behavior is presented here. 
