^^^^^^^^^^Given that the mind is a personal and essentially private construct, it is, then, essential to have at least a vision of how particular experiences from the individual's life relate to that personal construction of mind.  The requirement can not be avoided when the experiences involve the interaction of one person with another -- as do competitive games.  What I propose here is a description, not a theory; it is not a mere description, however, but one with aspirations.   Let me explain.  One outstanding contribution of Winston's early work (1975) was his observation that a description, through processes of part and relation emphasis, could be elevated to the status of a concept.  He presented an example of an object description, of a particular arch, which I would say initially aspired to be a concept of that class of objects.  We could call such an aspiring description an UR-concept of an arch.  (I apply this German prefix to mean "the primitive origin of a thing".)  What I struggle to produce here is, similarly, an ur-theory of how social experiences generate the personal construction of the individual mind.  We present this ur-theory through the example below and use it as a framework of interpretation for the body of the article.

1The Articulation of Complementary Roles0

^^^^^^^^^^Miriam has a long history of joke telling and invention (Lawler, 1977).  She plays with her infant sister, Peggy, often because she enjoys the play and often because she is "stuck" with her while we parents are otherwise occupied.  (The point is that their relation is basically amicable but also more than that.)  Peggy imitates us and her siblings and has begun imitating Miriam's knock-knock jokes. This was Peggy's first form of imitation:
