We will ask and try to answer such questions as: "what microworlds should we ascribe to Miriam ?"; "How are the microworlds organized ?"; and "How does the control structure of their organization develop^?"  In this context, microworlds are intended to represent the pattern-driven aspects of play.320

Connecting Networks^^^^^^^^^^ In this paper, we focus on the development of structure at a level of organization higher than microworlds.  The connecting networks whose elaboration we trace empirically derive inspiration and specific features from frames (Minsky, 1975), but  do not pretend to achieve the sophistication of Minsky's formulation.   We suppose that these connecting networks (or CON-NETS for short) develop from the progressive differentiation of very primitive activities.   Infants become engaged with and adept at turn taking behavior while very young; simple turn taking behavior, as witnessed in Tic tac toe, is assumed to be a later descendent of whatever earlier structures support such primitive activities.  We will trace precisely through behavior in particular experiences the incremental further specification of the con-net's control structure.  The Progressive Construction of Mind  describes processes creating new microworlds from interaction of their predecessors.  In this  paper, we will reconstruct an incident wherein a new microworld is constructed by the repeated working through of a fecund problem.  Finally, changes in the performance of the con-net and the microworlds are described as brought about by the interference of a microworld or a con-net function with the output of some other.  That is, the first output "shuts off" the output of some alternate substructure.  This inhibition is assumed to be a potential of the earlier structures which are extended in application to later developed structures.

